  fiTitle: Saa koskettaa
  fiPlace: Maaherranpuiston pallopatsas
  fiText: "Viktor Jansson ja Elli Wegelius seisovat Maaherranpuistossa, suihkul\xE4hteen
    \xE4\xE4ress\xE4. Suihkul\xE4hteess\xE4 on py\xF6riv\xE4 kivipallo. He eiv\xE4t
    katsele ymp\xE4rill\xE4 kuhisevaa el\xE4m\xE4\xE4, he ovat toisesta ajasta, ymp\xE4r\xF6iv\xE4t
    asiat eiv\xE4t merkitse sill\xE4 hetkell\xE4. He ovat niin keskittyneet n\xE4kem\xE4\xE4ns\xE4
    taiteeseen.\n\n\u201DTaide voi koskettaa monella tavalla, mutta taidetta voi
    my\xF6s koskettaa\u201D, Jansson sanoo ja rouva Wegelius py\xF6ritt\xE4\xE4 sile\xE4\xE4
    palloa, jota vesi n\xE4ytt\xE4\xE4 kannattelevan.\n\n\u201DSe on kuin maapallo
    avaruudessa, paikoillaan mink\xE4\xE4n kannattelemattomana\u201D, h\xE4n h\xE4mm\xE4stelee.\n\nSamalla
    paikalle kirmailee lapsia, jotka laittavat pallon py\xF6rim\xE4\xE4n uudelleen
    ja uudelleen.\n\n\u201DKuka t\xE4m\xE4n on laittanut t\xE4h\xE4n\u201D, kysyy
    lapsi \xE4\xE4neen.\n\n\u201DSen on valmistanut Savitaipaleen kiviveist\xE4m\xF6.
    Siell\xE4 on ollut taitava ihminen, hionut kiven ja tehnyt siit\xE4 kauniin.\u201D\n\nLapsi
    hymyilee. Rouva Wegelius pohtii, muistaako lapsi tuon hetken my\xF6hemmin. Ehk\xE4
    h\xE4n palaa joskus aikuisena pallon luo.\n\n\u201DKyll\xE4\u201D, Jansson vastaa
    kuin ajatukset lukien, \u201Dtaide luo muistoja ja toimii ankkurina menneisiin
    aikoihin ja paikkoihin.\u201D"
  enTitle: Touching allowed
  enPlace: Ball statue at Maaherranpuisto Park
  enText: "Viktor Jansson and Elli Wegelius are standing by a fountain at a park.
    The fountain features a rotating stone ball. They are oblivious to the life bustling
    around them as they come from another time, and what is around them does not
    matter at this moment. They are so deeply concentrated on the art before them.\n\n\"Art
    can touch you in so many ways, but art can also be touched\", says Jansson, as
    Mrs Wegelius rotates the smooth ball that seems to be carried by water.\n\n\"This
    is like the earth, floating in space, without being supported by anything,\u201D
    she says, amazed.\n\nAt that very moment, children come running and rotate the
    ball again and again.\n\n\"I wonder who put this here\" one of the children utters.\n\n\"It
    has been made by a stone-carving workshop in the village of Savitaipale. There
    was a skilled worker there who grinded the stone and made it beautiful.\u201D\n\nThe
    child smiles. Mrs Wegelius wonders whether the child will remember this moment
    later. Maybe he will return to the ball sometime as a grown-up.\n\n\"Yes\", Jansson
    says, as if reading her mind: \"art creates memories and connects people to times
    and places that are long gone.\u201D"
